weewx-rtl433-mqtt
Distributed under terms of the GPLv3

This is a driver for weewx that captures rtl_433 events from an MQTT broker.
It is inspired by weewx-sdr (https://github.com/matthewwall/weewx-sdr) but
takes a different approach: rtl_433 runs elsewhere - on a remote host, in a
container, or wherever the SDR dongle lives - and publishes JSON events to
MQTT.  This driver subscribes to those events and feeds them into weewx.

If you want weewx to drive rtl_433 directly via a local USB dongle, use
weewx-sdr instead.  This driver complements it; it does not replace it.


===============================================================================
Architecture

  [SDR host]  rtl_433 -F "mqtt://broker:1883,events"
                          |
                          v
                  [MQTT broker]
                          |
                          | subscribe rtl_433/+/events
                          v
  [weewx host]  user.rtl433mqtt  ->  sensor_map  ->  weewx database

The driver does no demodulation - rtl_433 has already turned the radio
into structured JSON before the message hits the broker.  All this driver
does is subscribe to the broker, normalize a couple of fields (battery,
optional unit conversion), and pass the result to weewx via the
sensor_map.


===============================================================================
Installation

0) install pre-requisites

  a) install weewx
      http://weewx.com/docs
  b) install rtl_433 on the host with the SDR dongle
      https://github.com/merbanan/rtl_433
  c) install paho-mqtt on the weewx host
      pip install paho-mqtt
  d) you need an MQTT broker reachable from both hosts (e.g. mosquitto)

1) install the driver

  weectl extension install /path/to/weewx-rtl433-mqtt

2) configure the driver

  weectl station reconfigure --driver=user.rtl433mqtt --no-prompt

3) start rtl_433 on the SDR host with mqtt output

  rtl_433 -M utc -F "mqtt://BROKER_HOST:1883,events"

  The 'events' suffix tells rtl_433 to publish the full JSON event
  (one publish per detection) to a topic of the form:

    rtl_433/<HOSTNAME>/events

4) discover your sensors using the standalone test mode (next section)

5) edit the [RTL433MQTT] section of weewx.conf with your sensor_map

6) start weewx

  sudo systemctl start weewx


===============================================================================
Recommended workflow - using test mode to build a sensor_map

The fastest path from "rtl_433 is publishing" to "data flowing into weewx"
is to use the standalone test mode iteratively:

a) start rtl_433 publishing to your broker (Installation step 3)

b) run the driver in test mode without a sensor_map:

     python3 /path/to/weewx-rtl433-mqtt/bin/user/rtl433mqtt.py \
         --host BROKER_HOST

   For each detected event you'll see lines like:

     === event 1 ===
     raw    : {"time":"2024-01-15 10:23:45","model":"Acurite-Tower",
               "id":11041,"channel":"B","battery_ok":1,
               "temperature_C":22.5,"humidity":45}
     parsed : {'dateTime': 1705314225, 'usUnits': 16,
               'channel.11041.Acurite-Tower': 'B',
               'temperature_C.11041.Acurite-Tower': 22.5,
               'humidity.11041.Acurite-Tower': 45,
               'battery.11041.Acurite-Tower': 0, ...}

c) note the keys in the 'parsed' dict - those are the exact
   <field>.<id>.<model> strings to use in your [[sensor_map]].
   Identify which sensor is which by powering them up one at a time
   (or by checking the labels on the sensor housings) and noting the id.

d) write [[sensor_map]] entries (see "Configuration - the sensor_map"
   below for examples).

e) re-run the test mode pointed at your in-progress weewx.conf:

     python3 /path/to/rtl433mqtt.py --config /path/to/weewx.conf

   Each event now also prints a 'mapped:' line with the exact dict
   weewx would receive.  Iterate on the sensor_map until you see the
   mappings you want.

f) install the driver (Installation step 1) if you haven't already,
   and start weewx.

The test mode does not require weewx to be installed on the machine
running it, so you can iterate on a laptop while weewx runs elsewhere.


===============================================================================
Configuration - the sensor_map

Each entry in [[sensor_map]] maps a weewx database field to a tuple
identifying the source field on a specific sensor:

  <weewx_field> = <rtl_433_field>.<sensor_id>.<rtl_433_model>

NOTE: the field part uses the rtl_433 unit suffix that matches your
unit_system setting.  With unit_system = METRIC (default), use
temperature_C / rain_mm / wind_avg_km_h.  With unit_system = US, the
driver renames those fields automatically, so you map to
temperature_F / rain_in / wind_avg_mi_h.

NOTE: the model part is rtl_433's 'model' field verbatim
(e.g. 'Acurite-Tower' with a hyphen).  This is NOT the same as
weewx-sdr's PacketClassName-style identifier - sensor maps cannot be
copied between the two drivers without translation.


# Example 1: a single Acurite Tower sensor

For a published event like:
  {"model":"Acurite-Tower","id":11041,"channel":"B","battery_ok":1,
   "temperature_C":22.5,"humidity":45}

[RTL433MQTT]
    driver = user.rtl433mqtt
    host = mqtt.local
    [[sensor_map]]
        outTemp           = temperature_C.11041.Acurite-Tower
        outHumidity       = humidity.11041.Acurite-Tower
        outBatteryStatus  = battery.11041.Acurite-Tower


# Example 2: Acurite Atlas (wind, temp, humidity, rain, UV, lux)

The Atlas emits multiple message types (37/38/39) covering different
fields.  rtl_433 publishes one event per message type, all with the
same id.  Map them all into one virtual weewx sensor:

[RTL433MQTT]
    [[sensor_map]]
        outTemp     = temperature_C.896.Acurite-Atlas
        outHumidity = humidity.896.Acurite-Atlas
        windSpeed   = wind_avg_km_h.896.Acurite-Atlas
        windDir     = wind_dir_deg.896.Acurite-Atlas
        rain_total  = rain_mm.896.Acurite-Atlas
        UV          = uv.896.Acurite-Atlas
        luminosity  = lux.896.Acurite-Atlas


# Example 3: Acurite Lightning detector (6045M)

This sensor emits a cumulative strike_count and a storm distance.  Use
the deltas section to turn the cumulative count into a per-period
lightning_strike_count.

[RTL433MQTT]
    [[sensor_map]]
        outTemp                = temperature_C.151.Acurite-6045M
        outHumidity            = humidity.151.Acurite-6045M
        lightning_strike_count = strike_count.151.Acurite-6045M
        lightning_distance     = storm_dist.151.Acurite-6045M
    [[deltas]]
        # the default already does this, shown here for clarity:
        lightning_strike_count = strike_count


# Example 4: Fine Offset rain gauge (cumulative rain_mm)

[RTL433MQTT]
    [[sensor_map]]
        rain_total = rain_mm.38.Fineoffset-WH1080
        windSpeed  = wind_avg_km_h.38.Fineoffset-WH1080
        windDir    = wind_dir_deg.38.Fineoffset-WH1080
    [[deltas]]
        rain = rain_total


# Example 5: combining several sensors in one map

[RTL433MQTT]
    driver      = user.rtl433mqtt
    host        = mqtt.local
    unit_system = METRIC
    [[sensor_map]]
        # outdoor weather (Acurite Tower outside)
        outTemp           = temperature_C.11041.Acurite-Tower
        outHumidity       = humidity.11041.Acurite-Tower
        outBatteryStatus  = battery.11041.Acurite-Tower

        # indoor sensor (Acurite Tower inside)
        inTemp            = temperature_C.5585.Acurite-Tower
        inHumidity        = humidity.5585.Acurite-Tower

        # rain gauge
        rain_total        = rain_mm.38.Fineoffset-WH1080

        # lightning detector
        lightning_strike_count = strike_count.151.Acurite-6045M
        lightning_distance     = storm_dist.151.Acurite-6045M
    [[deltas]]
        rain                   = rain_total
        lightning_strike_count = strike_count


# Glob-style patterns

Each of the three components supports fnmatch-style globs.  This is
useful when you have multiple identical sensors, or when you don't want
to pin to a specific id:

    [[sensor_map]]
        # any Acurite Tower's temperature, regardless of id
        outTemp = temperature_C.*.Acurite-Tower

        # specific id, any model
        inTemp  = temperature_C.5585.*

        # any rain_mm field on any model whose name contains 'Rain'
        rain_total = rain_mm.*.*Rain*

If you have two sensors of the same model and need to distinguish them,
list each id explicitly rather than relying on globs.


===============================================================================
Configuration - MQTT connection

[RTL433MQTT]
    driver = user.rtl433mqtt
    host = localhost                       # required
    port = 1883                            # default 1883
    topic = rtl_433/+/events               # default
    # username =                           # optional
    # password =                           # optional
    # tls = false                          # optional, default false
    # client_id =                          # optional

To consume only events from a specific rtl_433 host, set the topic to
the exact path rather than using the wildcard:

    topic = rtl_433/sdr-host.local/events

This is useful if multiple SDR hosts publish to the same broker and you
want different weewx instances to see different feeds.

# Example: TLS broker with auth on a non-standard port

[RTL433MQTT]
    driver   = user.rtl433mqtt
    host     = mqtt.example.com
    port     = 8883
    tls      = true
    username = weewx
    password = SECRET
    topic    = rtl_433/+/events


===============================================================================
Configuration - unit_system

The driver claims one unit system for every event it produces, so weewx
sees a coherent stream.  rtl_433 mostly emits SI units (_C, _mm, _km_h),
so the default is METRIC and no conversion happens.

If you prefer your weewx configured for US units, set unit_system = US
and the driver will automatically rename and convert any of the
following suffixes on its way out:

    _C    <->  _F     (degrees)
    _mm   <->  _in    (length)
    _km_h <->  _mi_h  (speed)
    _kph  <->  _mph   (speed, alternate label)
    _hPa  <->  _inHg  (pressure)

# Example: same Acurite Tower sensor, configured for US units

[RTL433MQTT]
    driver      = user.rtl433mqtt
    unit_system = US
    [[sensor_map]]
        outTemp     = temperature_F.11041.Acurite-Tower
        outHumidity = humidity.11041.Acurite-Tower

(With unit_system = METRIC the same sensor would be mapped via
 temperature_C.11041.Acurite-Tower.  The id and model parts are the
 same; only the field suffix changes.)

A sensor that natively emits a mixed unit set (e.g. temperature_F and
wind_avg_km_h in the same packet) will produce one converted field and
one already-correct field after this pass; both are exposed in the
parsed event.


===============================================================================
Configuration - deltas

Some sensors publish cumulative counters (rain since startup, lifetime
strike count).  WeeWX expects per-period observations.  The [[deltas]]
section indicates which cumulative fields should be split into deltas:

[RTL433MQTT]
    [[deltas]]
        rain                   = rain_total
        lightning_strike_count = strike_count

The default knows about rain and lightning strikes:

    rain                   <- rain_total
    lightning_strike_count <- strike_count

For this to work, the sensor_map must map a cumulative field onto the
RIGHT-HAND name in the deltas pair, e.g.:

    [[sensor_map]]
        rain_total   = rain_mm.38.Fineoffset-WH1080
        strike_count = strike_count.151.Acurite-6045M
    [[deltas]]
        rain                   = rain_total
        lightning_strike_count = strike_count

NOTE: the very first event after weewx restarts has no "previous"
counter to compare against, so the delta is None for that first event.
Subsequent events get the difference from the prior counter value.

NOTE: if a counter rolls over or decreases (e.g. rtl_433 restarts and
the sensor reports a lower cumulative), the delta is set to None and
the counter resets - no spurious negative numbers reach weewx.


===============================================================================
Configuration - logging

[RTL433MQTT]
    driver = user.rtl433mqtt
    log_unknown_sensors  = false   # log payloads we cannot parse as JSON
    log_unmapped_sensors = false   # log packets that match no sensor_map entry
    log_packets          = true    # log every yielded packet at debug level

Set log_unmapped_sensors = true while you're building your sensor_map -
events that match no entry will be logged at info level so you can see
exactly what they look like in the syslog.


===============================================================================
Standalone test mode

The driver can be run directly to exercise the full parse -> sensor_map
-> deltas pipeline against a live MQTT broker, without needing a weewx
install on the test machine.  Useful for:

  - figuring out the exact <field>.<id>.<model> strings for your sensors
  - verifying that a sensor_map you wrote actually picks up the right fields
  - confirming the unit_system option is doing what you expect
  - validating cumulative -> delta conversion before going live

Requires: paho-mqtt (always), and configobj only if you use --config.
weewx itself is NOT required.

# Example A: just see what's being published, no mapping

  python3 rtl433mqtt.py --host BROKER_HOST

# Example B: exercise a sensor_map by pointing at your real weewx.conf

  python3 rtl433mqtt.py --config /etc/weewx/weewx.conf

  Each event prints:
    raw    : <as published>
    parsed : <after _parse_event>
    mapped : <after sensor_map + deltas>   (or "<no sensor_map match>")

# Example C: config-driven but override the broker host (e.g. testing
#            the same sensor_map against a dev broker)

  python3 rtl433mqtt.py --config /etc/weewx/weewx.conf --host dev.local

# Example D: skip mapping even when --config provides one (just validate
#            parsing and unit conversion)

  python3 rtl433mqtt.py --config /etc/weewx/weewx.conf --no-map

# Example E: TLS broker on a non-standard port with auth

  python3 rtl433mqtt.py --host secure.broker.local --port 8883 --tls \
                       --username weewx --password SECRET

# Example F: filter to a specific rtl_433 host's events

  python3 rtl433mqtt.py --host BROKER_HOST \
                       --topic rtl_433/sdr-host.local/events

All recognized flags:

  --config FILE       weewx.conf-style file with an [RTL433MQTT] section
  --host HOST         broker address
  --port PORT         broker port (default 1883)
  --topic TOPIC       MQTT topic (default rtl_433/+/events)
  --username USER     broker auth username
  --password PASS     broker auth password
  --tls               use TLS for the broker connection
  --unit-system SYS   US or METRIC (default METRIC)
  --no-map            skip sensor_map even if --config provides one
  --version           print driver version and exit

You can also subscribe to the broker outside this driver to confirm
events are arriving at all:

  mosquitto_sub -h BROKER_HOST -t 'rtl_433/+/events' -v


===============================================================================
Troubleshooting

# "I see events in mosquitto_sub but my sensor_map doesn't pick anything up"

Check unit_system.  If your map says temperature_F.11041.Acurite-Tower
but unit_system is METRIC (the default), the parsed field is named
temperature_C and the map won't find a match.  Switch unit_system to US,
or change the map to temperature_C.

To confirm, run test mode against your config and look at the parsed
keys:

  python3 rtl433mqtt.py --config /path/to/weewx.conf

If parsed keys end in _C and your map says _F (or vice versa), that's
the mismatch.

# "I get '<no sensor_map match>' for every event"

The id or model string in your map probably doesn't match what rtl_433
actually publishes.  Cross-check by looking at the parsed dict keys in
test mode (Example A above) - the right-hand parts of those keys are
the exact id and model strings to use.  Common stumbles:

  - id is decimal, not hex.  rtl_433 emits id as a number (e.g. 11041);
    weewx-sdr uses 4-char hex (e.g. 2b21).  Use the decimal here.
  - model is hyphenated.  rtl_433's modern model field is e.g.
    "Acurite-Tower", not "Acurite tower sensor" or "AcuriteTowerPacket".

# "outBatteryStatus is always 0 (or always 1)"

The driver follows the WeeWX convention: 0 = battery ok, 1 = battery low.
rtl_433 emits this in several different ways depending on sensor:

    battery_ok   = 1     ->  battery = 0  (ok)
    battery_ok   = 0     ->  battery = 1  (low)
    battery_low  = 0     ->  battery = 0  (ok)
    battery_low  = 1     ->  battery = 1  (low)
    battery      = "OK"  ->  battery = 0  (ok)

If you see "always 0" on a sensor whose battery is actually low, the
sensor may not be sending its low-battery flag yet (some Acurite units
trigger it only below ~4V).

# "rain is None on the first event after I restart weewx"

Expected.  Deltas need a previous counter value to compute against, and
the very first event has no prior value.  Subsequent events return the
difference.  WeeWX handles None gracefully - the LOOP record will lack
the rain field, and the next archive record will pick up real values.

# "events publish at the wrong time / hour off"

rtl_433's "time" field uses whatever the rtl_433 -M flag specifies.
Use '-M utc' (recommended; the driver assumes UTC) so timestamps are
consistent regardless of which host the SDR is on.

# "the broker connection drops periodically"

The driver uses paho-mqtt's automatic reconnect (1-120s backoff).  If
disconnects are frequent, check the broker keepalive (the driver uses
60s) and any network/firewall idle timeouts in between.

# "ImportError: paho-mqtt is required"

  pip install paho-mqtt

This is needed both for live (driver-mode) operation and for the
standalone test mode, since both connect to a real broker.

# "ImportError / SystemExit: configobj is required"

Only thrown when test mode is invoked with --config.  Either:
  pip install configobj
or run test mode without --config (passing flags directly).
